SIMPLE: homely
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Homely
<hw>Home"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Homelier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Homeliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[From <er>Home</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Belonging to, or having the
characteristics of, home; domestic; familiar; intimate.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With all these men I was right <qex>homely</qex>, and communed
with, them long and oft.</q> <rj><qau>Foxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their <qex>homely</qex> joys, and destiny obscure.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Plain; unpretending; rude in appearance; unpolished;
<as>as, a <ex>homely</ex> garment; a <ex>homely</ex> house;
<ex>homely</ex> fare; <ex>homely</ex> manners.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now Strephon daily entertains⟦br⟧
His Chloe in the <qex>homeliest</qex> strains.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of plain or coarse features; uncomely; ugly; --
usually used of people, especially women; -- contrary to
<ant>handsome</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>None so <qex>homely</qex> but loves a looking-glass.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Homely</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Homely
<hw>Home"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Plainly; rudely; coarsely;
<as>as, <ex>homely</ex> dressed</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Homelyn</ent>⟦br⟧
